  "prompt": "What is the difference between O- and O+?",
  "response": "The terms \"O-\" and \"O+\" refer to different blood types within the ABO blood group system and the Rh factor system.\n\n1. **ABO Blood Group System**: \n   - The \"O\" indicates that the person has type O blood, which means their red blood cells do not have A or B antigens on their surface.\n  \n2. **Rh Factor**: \n   - The \"+\" or \"-\" denotes the presence or absence of the Rh factor, specifically the D antigen. \n   - \"O+\" means the blood type is O and the Rh factor is positive, indicating that the Rh antigen is present.\n   - \"O-\" means the blood type is O and the Rh factor is negative, indicating that the Rh antigen is absent.\n\nIn terms of blood transfusions, O- blood is often considered the universal donor type for red blood cells since it lacks A, B, and Rh antigens, making it less likely to cause a reaction in recipients of any blood type. On the other hand, O+ blood can be given to any Rh-positive individuals but not to Rh-negative individuals.",
